  "prompt": "How do I give my girlfriend space / stop the feeling of having my soul sucked out for the seconds I'm not with her?",
  "response": "It\u2019s great that you\u2019re reflecting on this and wanting to create a healthy balance in your relationship. Giving your girlfriend space and managing your own emotions when you're apart are important for both of you to thrive individually and as a couple. Here are some practical tips:\n\n---\n\n### **How to Give Your Girlfriend Space**\n1. **Respect Her Needs**  \n   - If she asks for space, respect it without taking it personally. Space doesn\u2019t mean she doesn\u2019t care about you; it\u2019s about her needing time to recharge or focus on herself.  \n   - Avoid bombarding her with messages or trying to fill every moment of her day.\n\n2. **Encourage Her Individuality**  \n   - Support her hobbies, interests, and time with friends. Show genuine enthusiasm for her doing things without you.  \n   - This strengthens her sense of self and makes your time together more meaningful.\n\n3. **Focus on Your Own Life**  \n   - When you\u2019re apart, use the time to pursue your own passions, hobbies, or goals. This shows her that you\u2019re independent and self-sufficient, which is attractive and healthy.\n\n4. **Communicate Openly but Calmly**  \n   - If you\u2019re unsure about how much space she needs, have an honest conversation. Ask her what she needs and express your feelings without pressure or guilt.\n\n---\n\n### **How to Stop Feeling Like Your Soul is Being Sucked Out**\n1. **Work on Your Emotional Independence**  \n   - Practice self-soothing techniques like deep breathing, journaling, or mindfulness to manage the anxiety or emptiness you feel when you\u2019re apart.  \n   - Remind yourself that you\u2019re a whole person on your own, and your worth isn\u2019t tied to being with her.\n\n2. **Identify the Root of Your Dependence**  \n   - Reflect on why you feel so intensely when you\u2019re apart. Is it fear of abandonment? Loneliness? Low self-esteem? Understanding this can help you address it.  \n\n3. **Build a Support System**  \n   - Lean on friends, family, or a therapist for emotional support. Having other meaningful connections can reduce the pressure on your relationship.\n\n4. **Practice Gratitude for Solitude**  \n   - Shift your mindset to see time apart as an opportunity for growth, self-care , or pursuing personal interests.  \n   - Remind yourself that space can strengthen your relationship in the long run.\n\n5. **Engage in Distractions**  \n   - Fill your time with activities you enjoy\u2014exercise, read, watch a show, or learn something new. Staying busy can help you cope with the discomfort of being apart.\n\n---\n\n### **Remember:**\n- Healthy relationships thrive on balance. Giving each other space allows you to grow individually and come back together as stronger, more fulfilled partners.  \n- It\u2019s okay to miss her, but it\u2019s important not to let that feeling consume you. Use it as a reminder of how much you care, but also as motivation to nurture your own life.\n\nIf these feelings persist and feel overwhelming, consider speaking with a therapist to explore them further. You deserve to feel secure and fulfilled, both in and out of your relationship.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
